english:
  title: Preface to the Poetry Collection of Lord Purim
  author: Sung Hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Can poetry be spoken of so easily? Poetry emerges from the heart and takes shape in words—it is the very essence of language. By observing what words reveal, we may discern what lies within a person's soul. Generally speaking, those who have risen to high station speak with plain and measured words; those nurtured in luxury and comfort speak with excessive ornament; those who suffer poverty and find no place in the world speak with sorrow, resentment, and bitter refinement.

    Consider water: in peaceful flow, it runs without waves, stretching wide and deep, bottomless and unmeasurable. Yet when it meets a storm and strikes jagged cliffs, it roars and surges forth, unable to cease. Peaceful flow is the true nature of water; surely the violent torrent is not its nature, but rather a transformation forced upon it by uneven ground. The poetry of literary men follows this same principle.

    Yet why does the world not delight in what is peaceful, but rather in what is turbulent? It is because words of harmony are difficult to perfect, while words of sorrow and indignation easily achieve brilliance. Our nation is governed through the virtues of simplicity and depth, and our literary culture surpasses even the ancients. Every person of talent and skill finds use in the world, and none languish below with unvoiced grievances. Even the wealthy and noble pursue the Way through books and learning. The Lord of Wind-Moon Pavilion, as the elder of the royal house, embodied refinement and literary grace in his age—our subject stands as his equal in exchanging verses and composing together, his poems spreading through all mouths.

    His poetry is gentle and temperate, weighty and profound, free from pretense and excessive ornamentation. The ancients said, 'Gentleness and sincerity, depth and generosity—these are the teachings of poetry.' Has he not grasped poetry's true teaching? Confucius said, 'One of virtue must have words.' Is he not one of virtue? I once glimpsed his bearing—a jade-like countenance, brows and eyes painted as if by brush. Then I wished to sit in his discourse but could not. Now his words flow as flawlessly as his face, and through them his inner virtue shines clear.

    Had Heaven granted him longer years to grow unfailing in his art, surely he would have composed the grand verses that sing a nation's glory. Yet fate cut short his thread mid-course, and his talents could not fully bloom. What a loss! Now, at his son's request, I offer these humble words to praise his gifts and virtue, and to give voice to my own sorrow.
  footnotes:
    - Wind-Moon Pavilion (風月亭) refers to a notable literary figure from the royal house known for his refinement and poetic talent during this era.
    - The reference to 'Ya and Song' (雅頌) alludes to the highest forms of poetry in classical Chinese tradition, representing the pinnacle of poetic achievement.
    - This preface mourns the early death of Lord Purim while celebrating his poetic and moral accomplishments, written at the request of his son.
